The user wants me to fix a miscompilation in LLVM's `instcombine` pass.
The issue is that `instcombine` incorrectly transforms `select i1 %cond, i1 %cmp1, i1 %cmp2` into `xor i1 %cond, %cmp2`. This transformation is only valid if `%cmp1` is the logical negation of `%cmp2`.

The reproducer is:
```llvm
define i1 @test_select_inverse_samesign_false_arm_rhsc_same_sign(i64 %x, i64 %y, i1 %cond) {
  %cmp1 = icmp ult i64 %x, 11
  %cmp2 = icmp samesign ugt i64 %x, 10
  %sel = select i1 %cond, i1 %cmp1, i1 %cmp2
  ret i1 %sel
}
```

The transformation happens because `isKnownInversion(%cmp1, %cmp2)` returns true.
Looking at the implementation of `isKnownInversion` from the previous step:

```c++
bool llvm::isKnownInversion(const Value *X, const Value *Y) {
  // Handle X = icmp pred A, B, Y = icmp pred A, C.
  Value *A, *B, *C;
  ICmpInst::Predicate Pred1, Pred2;
  if (!match(X, m_ICmp(Pred1, m_Value(A), m_Value(B))) ||
      !match(Y, m_c_ICmp(Pred2, m_Specific(A), m_Value(C))))
    return false;

  if (B == C)
    return Pred1 == ICmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred2);

  // Try to infer the relationship from constant ranges.
  const APInt *RHSC1, *RHSC2;
  if (!match(B, m_APInt(RHSC1)) || !match(C, m_APInt(RHSC2)))
    return false;

  const auto CR1 = ConstantRange::makeExactICmpRegion(Pred1, *RHSC1);
  const auto CR2 = ConstantRange::makeExactICmpRegion(Pred2, *RHSC2);

  return CR1.inverse() == CR2;
}
```

In our case:
- `X` is `%cmp1 = icmp ult i64 %x, 11`
- `Y` is `%cmp2 = icmp samesign ugt i64 %x, 10`

The `m_ICmp` matcher only extracts the predicate (`ult`, `ugt`) and operands, but it doesn't capture the `samesign` flag. The `samesign` flag is a property of the `ICmpInst` itself, not the `ICmpInst::Predicate` enum.

The function `ConstantRange::makeExactICmpRegion` also only takes the predicate and the constant, and does not know about the `samesign` flag. This is the root cause of the problem. The `ConstantRange` logic correctly deduces that for non-negative numbers, `x <u 11` is the inverse of `x >u 10`, but it's unaware that the `samesign` flag on the second compare makes it false for all negative `x`, breaking the inversion.

The alive2 error log shows that for `x = -9223372036854775808` (INT64_MIN), `%cmp1` is false and `%cmp2` is also false (due to `samesign`), which are not inverses.

To fix this, `isKnownInversion` must be aware of the `samesign` flag. I will modify `isKnownInversion` to check if either of the comparisons has the `samesign` flag. If so, the `ConstantRange` based logic is unsafe, and we should bail out. This is a conservative but safe fix.

I will add a check for `isSameSign()` on both `ICmpInst`s.

```bash
sed -i '8523 a\
  if (cast<ICmpInst>(X)->isSameSign() || cast<ICmpInst>(Y)->isSameSign())\
    return false;\
' llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp
```

